result.execSummary:
The defendant Frederick J Haney was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Intimidate Victim/Dissuade Complaints [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse], a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 940.44(2).
  • Disorderly Conduct [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse - Infliction of Physical Pain or Injury], a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: Hearing on May 23, 2022 at 08:30 am.

10:26 AM Defendant Frederick J Haney in court, in custody, with attorney May Y Lee.   Michael Thurston appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Attorney Thurston is asking for a brief adjournment as the State's witness is unavailable today.  Attorney Lee states it is her understanding that the State's witness was unavailable today and would like to reserve her right to object at a later date.  The Court is going to proceed with the preliminary hearing today given the history of this case.  The Court takes a short recess at 10:29 AM to allow for the State to allow for a witness to review the criminal complaint and booking photo of the defendant in order to proceed.  Matter recalled at 10:35 AM with the same appearances.  City of Waukesha Police Department Detective Steven Guth sworn in and testifies on direct by Attorney Thurston.  Cross examination by Attorney Lee.  State rests.  State moves for bind over without argument.  Attorney Lee objects to bind over without argument and moves to dismiss.  Court finds probable cause to believe that a felony was committed and binds the defendant over for trial.  Waive reading of Information.   NOT GUILTY PLEA ENTERED.  Bail remains as fixed.  Attorney Lee enters a demand for a speedy trial.  Hearing scheduled for May 23, 2022 at 08:30 am.

09:18 AM Defendant Frederick J Haney in court, in custody, with attorney May Y Lee who appeared by Zoom.   Andrew Nesheim appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  All parties have agreed that some may have the hearing conducted remotely. This hearing has met the statutory standards for video conferencing.  Attorney Lee is asking for an adjournment of the preliminary hearing.  The Court makes a record as to how thoroughly disappointed with how this case has been handled.  Attorney Lee responds to the Court's concerns.  The Court will adjourn the preliminary hearing.  Time limits were previously waived.  Bail remains as fixed.  The Court orders Attorney Lee to appear in person at the next hearing.  Preliminary hearing scheduled for May 9, 2022 at 09:15 am.
